Flyer Activities
September 9 at 4:03 PM ¬∑

FLYER FACT: We were asked when did the Little Falls School District become known as the Flyers?

According to the Morrison County Historical Society, our mascot became the Flyers back in 1928. Before 1928, we did not have a mascot. Schools started choosing such nicknames in the late 1920's.

GO FLYERS!!!

If you haven't taken the time to fill out the Application for Educational Benefits form for our District, please do so.

There are two main ways to do this. The first option is to download this form, print it, fill it out by hand, and return it to school. The second option is to complete this through Skyward. Option #2 entails going to Skyward, clicking on Family Access, clicking on the Food Service tab, clicking on the Applications link, and then clicking on Add Application. You will then be prompted to read and answer the questions.

This form needs to be filled out every year.

Thank you! #FlyerPride

post_text:
Since October of 1989, Jeanine Pantzke has been employed by Little Falls Community Schools, but her role has changed! She is now the secretary at Dr. SG Knight. Before accepting her new position, Jeanine served as a playground paraprofessional, an educational paraprofessional, and a PCA. Additionally, she was involved with Project Reconnect and coached numerous Community Services activities after school.

When asked what excites her the most about her new role, Jeanine comments, ‚ÄúI have new challenges and duties, but it is most exciting that I get to work with the same wonderful staff and interact with the students. It will just be in a different capacity.‚Äù

When it is time to vacation, Jeanine prefers temperatures in the 80-degree range with a nice sandy beach nearby. She said this would be even better if Pink showed up to put on a concert. In her free time, Jeanine loves to be outdoors. She likes to walk, bike, boat, horseback ride, and garden, and she especially loves spending time with her family, friends, and pets.

Congratulations, Jeanine! #FlyerPride

post_text:
We are incredibly pleased to welcome Liz Czech to the District! A recent graduate of Winona State University, Liz joins the high school staff as a special education teacher. Liz shares, ‚ÄúI am excited to be joining a community that is close to home, and one that I am already very familiar with. The school district has already shown me kindness and given me a chance to expand my experience and education.‚Äù

To Liz, personalized learning means ‚Äúmeeting each student where they are at and adapting the curriculum to best fit their needs.‚Äù

When she has free time, Liz loves being outdoors. She especially enjoys spending time with friends while camping, fishing, or just sitting around a campfire. Liz says she really enjoyed hiking the mountains of Southwest Oregon, visiting the ocean, and exploring the small town shops. She would love to relive this experience if given the chance. Carrie Underwood is the musician Liz would most like to see in concert.

Welcome, Liz! #FlyerPride

Today, we are introducing Marissa Rapaway. Marissa graduated from SCSU last spring with a secondary math education degree and a minor in special education. She joins our District as a math teacher at the high school. Marissa is looking forward to working with the students and staff of the district.

To Marissa, personalized learning means ‚Äúthat each student can learn in a way that works for them. Every student learns best in a different way. Personalized learning allows the student to learn in a way that is tailored to their individual needs.‚Äù

When it‚Äôs time to relax, Marissa enjoys listening to music, watching movies, and completing jigsaw puzzles. She also is a fan of hunting, fishing, camping, and spending time with her family. A trip to Alaska complete with a glacier tour and dog sledding is on the top of Marissa‚Äôs list as a dream vacation.

Welcome, Marissa! #FlyerPride

We would like to extend a warm welcome to Haily Koopmeiners! Haily is our new speech language pathologist. She will be servicing students throughout the district, so she will be visible in many of our buildings. A recent graduate of the St. Cloud State Master‚Äôs program, Haily completed an internship with our district last year, and she said the opportunity to meet so many helpful, friendly, and passionate staff members most excites her about Little Falls Community Schools.

When asked to share her thoughts about personalized learning, Haily commented, ‚ÄúPersonalized learning is a very important part of working in a school environment. All students deserve to be taught in a way that they are able to learn best. Personalized learning provides students with the individualized teaching that they need to be successful.‚Äù

In Haily‚Äôs spare time, she enjoys fishing, water skiing, visiting friends, and playing with her puppy. If she could meet someone famous, her choice would be Shania Twain!

Welcome to the District, Haily! #FlyerPride

Morgan Zeise is extremely excited to be joining the staff at Lindbergh Elementary as a second-grade teacher. Morgan is a graduate of Wadena-Deer Creek High School and the University of North Dakota. Last year she worked as a paraprofessional and a substitute teacher in the Little Falls District. Through this experience, she found everyone to be extremely friendly, welcoming, and helpful.

Morgan believes personalized learning involves getting to know each student as an individual in order to understand their needs and interests. Once this relationship is formed, it is time to set goals, create a path to help students meet their goals, and celebrate together when goals are met!

When asked what she enjoys during her free time, Morgan shares, ‚ÄúI like to relax at the lake with a cup of coffee. I enjoy swimming, skiing and running. In the winter, I like to ice fish and skate at the outdoor rink.‚Äù If she could plan her dream vacation, she would love to go camping and hiking in the mountains of Banff in Alberta, Canada.

Welcome, Morgan! #FlyerPride

post_text:
Good evening. On Wednesday of this week, July 15, the District will be releasing our first version of Little Falls Community Schools' Reopening Plan for the 2020-2021 school year. The plan will focus mainly on the academic options that Little Falls Community Schools has been exploring and creating as mandated by the Minnesota Department of Education. As the Reopening Plan states, this first version is focusing on academics and what a school schedule could look like at our schools under the various reopening plans. In future weeks, the District is planning at least two major revisions to the Reopening Plan that will address many other aspects of returning students to school including:

Transportation
Food Service
Childcare
Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)
Social Distancing Standards, Protocol, and Signage
Health Screenings / Information
Protecting Vulnerable Populations
Hygiene Practices
Cleaning and Materials Handling
Response to Suspected or Confirmed Positive Cases of COVID-19
Activities / Athletics / Co-Curricular

Thank you. #FlyerPride

We are incredibly excited to bring you this week's "Field Trip Tuesday" because it is from Pine Grove Zoo! Abby (the zoo curator), Becky (the assistant director), and Erin (a zoo intern) welcomed us to the training demonstration. Watch as the adorable Morris and Eugene show off their skills during the training demonstration.

These spunky little porcupines have called the zoo their home for about a year now, and towards the end of this video, you will see how much they adore the people who care for them. One purpose of the training demonstrations is to work on relationship building between the animals and the keepers. We ‚ù§Ô∏è the power of relationships!

Thank you so much to all of the amazing people at Pine Grove Zoo for making this field trip possible. Check out their Facebook page and website (https://www.pinegrovezoo.com/) in order to learn all about the ways to enjoy and become involved with this local treasure! #Morris&Eugene #FieldTripTuesday #FlyerPride

post_text:
So, where were we? We were at Belle Prairie Park.

Belle Prairie Park is open from 10:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m. daily. Visitors to the park can hike, play disc golf, use the playground, fish from shore, and enjoy the many picnic areas including a sheltered area. It is important to note, the shelter area cannot be reserved. It is available on a first-come, first-served basis. Get out and enjoy this beauty! #WhereWereWeWednesday #FlyerPride

PRIZES, PRIZES, PRIZES

As we wrap up the school year, we want to THANK YOU for all that you have done these past 8 weeks. We realize it has not been an easy transition, but we are so thankful for the partnerships that have come out of this, and look forward to those partnerships continuing in the years to come.

This video focuses on ways to support math and reading (mostly math) at home by creating simple routines. Although Distance Learning is wrapping up, these routines will help ensure that your student continues to make gains over the summer.

ANOTHER CHANCE TO WIN PRIZES :)

We need your help!!!

As educators and a school systems, we are always working to improve and get better, just like we ask our students to do. We are currently creating a Parent Advisory Committee to help us do just that. This committee would meet twice a year (perhaps virtually), and would give us necessary feedback and ideas to continue to improve the way we are doing Title One at Little Falls Community Elementary Schools.

Watch this quick video to learn more.

If you would be willing to be part of this valuable committee, please complete this quick form linked in the comment section below..

Enter to Win by:
1. Watching the Video

Future plans: I plan to go to St. Cloud Tech and become a dental hygienist. #FlyerPride

post_text:
We are excited to celebrate our seniors on Friday, May 15! Little Falls Community High School, the Grad Bash committee, and the city of Little Falls are recognizing the seniors on this day. Seniors, please come to the high school front loop off 5th Avenue SE (the horseshoe) between 2:00-7:00 p.m. to receive your cap and gown, your yearbook, your Grad Bash prizes, your scholarships, and any awards received in the month of May.

At this time, if you no longer need your iPad or specific materials for your classes, you will be able to return them to the high school. If you still need them for the last week of school, you can keep materials, and we will make other arrangements for collecting items.

Note: ALL LFCHS graduating seniors will be receiving prizes from the Grad Bash committee. If you paid for Grad Bash, your money will be refunded.

#WeLoveOurSeniors #FlyerPride

post_text:
Every year, teachers from our District are recognized at Sourcewell's Educators of Excellence Awards spring event. These teachers are celebrated for their dedication, hard work, and leadership.

Congratulations to this year's recipients: Kelly Mertens from Dr. Knight Elementary, Brittany Varner from Lincoln Elementary, Peggy Rekstad from Lindbergh Elementary, Ryan Tenold from LFCMS, and Deb Yliniemi-Ahlin from LFCHS!

We are inspired by you! #FlyerPride
text:
Every year, teachers from our District are recognized at Sourcewell's Educators of Excellence Awards spring event. These teachers are celebrated for their dedication, hard work, and leadership.

Congratulations to this year's recipients: Kelly Mertens from Dr. Knight Elementary, Brittany Varner from Lincoln Elementary, Peggy Rekstad from Lindbergh Elementary, Ryan Tenold from LFCMS, and Deb Yliniemi-Ahlin from LFCHS!

post_text:
Tonight is Sourcewell's annual Educators of Excellence program. This year's theme is Creating a Legacy. Our District is well-represented by this year's Team of Educational Excellence! Congratulations to Neil Andruschak, Angie Bellig, Reid Bellig, Susan Benjamin, Tony Bergman, Melonie Brown, Andy Ward, Kyle Connelly, Caitlin Skluzacek, Jill Tomala, and Glennda Davis for being named the Team of Excellence for your work as the Digital Convergence Advanced Cohort for the 2019-2020 academic year.

Your commitment to personalized learning through learner voice and choice is innovative and admirable, and your role as mentors for your peers is invaluable. Congratulations! #FlyerPride

post_text: Today Governor Tim Walz announced that Minnesota schools will not reopen this school year and that Distance Learning will continue throughout the rest of the school year. So going forward for Little Falls Community Schools, that means that we will continue operating as we've done for the past six weeks through the end of the scheduled school year of May 27. We cannot and will not make any decisions on anything yet in June, July, or August; we will continue to seek guidance from the Governor's office, Department of Education, Department of Health, and the State and Federal Governments. One other announcement related to the school year: Friday, May 1, and Monday, May 4, will now be Professional Development Days for teachers and will not be school days for students. However, Tier I & Tier II childcare will be provided for the families currently using it...and we will be providing food delivery through our bus routes on both May 1 and May 4. Please contact your school office or me with any questions or concerns you may have.

post_text:
Mary Bartlett, Gail Johnson, and Will Threlkeld have been overseeing the meal delivery program and are here to introduce our next social media challenge. Your objective is to come up with a unique use for the hinged trays that come home filled with daily meals. Entries can be functional and/or artistic in nature.

Please submit your photos to info@lfalls.k12.mn.us by Monday, April 27 at midnight. We can't wait to see your creativity! Please include the name of your child(ren) and the grade. We will be posting photos of the submissions and drawing two entries to receive gift certificates for The Falls Ballroom Banquet & Catering Services for takeout meals.

#FlyerPride

The District's leadership team has developed a social media challenge called #LeadForwardLocally. The purpose is to support local business within a community. The challenge is for leaders within an organization to go out in the community and purchase gift cards to support their local businesses and then come up with a creative challenge on social media to give the cards away to the community. As a leadership team we are challenging the leaders from @Morrison County Government Center, Pillager Schools, Royalton Public Schools, and Wadena-Deer Creek Public Schools to participate and #LeadForwardLocally

#FlyerPride

The District's leadership team has developed a social media challenge called #LeadForwardLocally. The purpose is to support local business within a community. The challenge is for leaders within an organization to go out in the community and purchase gift cards to support their local businesses and then come up with a creative challenge on social media to give the cards away to the community. As a leadership team we are challenging the leaders from @Morrison County Government Center, Pillager Schools, Royalton Public Schools, and Wadena-Deer Creek Public Schools to participate and #LeadForwardLocally

Name: Claire Zack
Activities/sports/clubs: Cross Country, Nordic Skiing, Track, Musical, Jubileers, and LINK
Favorite memory from school: Senior year Homecoming; it was the funnest week ever with the best people ever.
Favorite high school class: AP Econ with Mr.Stockard
Favorite pastime/hobby: With all my new-found free time, I love getting active and working as well as painting and doing mini art projects
Advice to younger students about making high school successful and memorable: Don't take anything for granted! Trust me, your whole school career can change in the blink of an eye, so make the most of every single day you have with your friends, teachers, and coaches. Don't wait until your senior year to try new things, just go for it!
Future plans: Attending the Carlson School of Management at The University of Minnesota, Twin Cities, and pursuing a degree in marketing. #FlyerPride
